Kubernetes Example

Stable Deployment:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app-v1

spec:
  replicas: 9

  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
      version: v1

  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
        version: v1

    spec:
      containers:
      - name: app
        image: nginx:1.25
-------------------------------------------------

Canary Deployment:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app-v2

spec:
  replicas: 1

  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
      version: v2

  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
        version: v2

    spec:
      containers:
      - name: app
        image: nginx:1.26
Service
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-service

spec:
  selector:
    app: myapp

  ports:
  - port: 80
---------------------------------------------------------
Notice:

The Service selects only:

selector:
  app: myapp

It doesn't care about:

version: v1
version: v2

Both deployments have:

app: myapp

Therefore, both receive traffic.

How Traffic Flows
User
   │
   ▼
Service
   │
   ├─────────────┐
   │             │
   ▼             ▼
v1 Pod        v2 Pod

The Service sends requests to both sets of pods because both match the selector.

Gradual Rollout

Step 1

v1 = 9 Pods

v2 = 1 Pod

Step 2

v1 = 7 Pods

v2 = 3 Pods

Step 3

v1 = 5 Pods

v2 = 5 Pods

Step 4

v1 = 0 Pods

v2 = 10 Pods

Delete:

kubectl delete deployment app-v1
Rollback

If Version 2 has problems:

9 Pods v1

1 Pod v2

Delete v2:

kubectl delete deployment app-v2

Users immediately return to Version 1.

Canary vs Rolling Update
Feature	Rolling Update	Canary
Two versions run together	Briefly	Yes
Traffic split	Not intentionally	Yes
Easy rollback	Yes	Yes
Test with small audience	No	Yes
Monitor before full release	Limited	Yes
Canary vs Blue-Green
Blue-Green	Canary
Two full environments	Two versions with partial rollout
Switch all traffic at once	Gradually shift traffic
More infrastructure required	Less infrastructure
Fast rollback	Fast rollback
Real-World Tools

Canary deployments are commonly implemented using:

Kubernetes Deployments (basic pod-percentage approach)
NGINX Ingress (weighted routing)
Istio (fine-grained traffic splitting, e.g., 95%/5%)
Linkerd (service mesh)
Argo Rollouts (advanced canary automation)
Flagger (automated progressive delivery)
Interview Questions
What is a Canary Deployment?

A Canary Deployment is a deployment strategy where a new application version is released to a small subset of users first.
After monitoring health, performance, and error rates, traffic is gradually shifted to the new version. If issues are detected,
the deployment is rolled back with minimal impact.

Why is Canary better than deploying to everyone immediately?
Reduces deployment risk.
Limits the number of affected users.
Allows real production testing.
Enables fast rollback.
Does Kubernetes support Canary Deployment out of the box?

Basic canary: Yes. You can run two Deployments with the same Service selector and control the approximate traffic by changing replica counts.

Advanced canary: For precise traffic percentages (like exactly 95%/5%), automated promotion, or analysis-based rollouts, you typically use tools such as Istio, NGINX Ingress, or Argo Rollouts. Kubernetes itself does not provide fine-grained traffic weighting between pods.
